<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-003-320 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 564 014</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Dec 2 1991 v25 n48 p39(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Calif. college takes graphic approach to ease of use. (San JoaquinDelta College in California)(case study)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Daly, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>San Joaquin Delta College gives nearly 500 faculty and staffmembers easy access to large amounts of mainframe data whilepreserving its investment in installed mainframe, minicomputer andmicrocomputer systems.andP;  The campuswide network includes a UnisysB6930 mainframe, three DEC VAX minicomputers, nine file serversand 170 Apple Macintosh workstations.andP;  A customized 'Virtual Desk'program modifies the graphical user interface on the Macintoshesto put icons for mainframe and minicomputer links on the screen.andO;Its desktop metaphor extends to a 'wall' with a calendar and'envelopes' that represent E-mail; the 'sun' in the office windows'sets' at the end of the day.andP;  Virtual Desk can be used to accessstudent records, university policies, departmental budgets andother information from the mainframe and minicomputer systems.andO;Claris Corp's Hypercard was used to create the databaseinterfaces, and on-screen objects act as stand-alone tools thatusers can customized.andP;  Managers say that Virtual Desk has alreadypaid for itself in increased productivity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer systems integrationCase StudyColleges and UniversitiesMultivendor SystemsLocal area networksMicro-Mainframe CommunicationMicro-Minicomputer CommunicationInformation Storage and RetrievalProductivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>